      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u help me understand how a force majeure clause works if there is a sudden regional power grid failure? like if the supplier cant deliver because the power went out for everyone in that area, does that count as an unforeseeable event under most standard contracts?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A force majeure clause is a contractual provision that excuses parties from performing their obligations when an unforeseen event occurs, such as a regional power grid failure. In your scenario, a sudden power outage that prevents the supplier from delivering goods or services could indeed be considered an unforeseen event under most standard contracts. However, it's essential to review the specific language of the contract, as the definition of \"force majeure\" can vary from one contract to another.",
