    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "one more thing, how does the concept of \"mitigation\" play into this? if the grid fails but the supplier could have used backup generators if they'd prepared better, does that mean they lose the force majeure protection entirely even if the outage itself was a total surprise?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of mitigation is a crucial aspect of force majeure clauses. If the supplier could have reasonably mitigated the effects of the grid failure by taking measures such as using backup generators, and they failed to do so, they may be deemed to have contributed to the event and therefore waived their force majeure protection. This is because the supplier's failure to take reasonable precautions can be seen as a breach of their obligations under the contract. However, if the supplier can demonstrate that they had no knowledge of the potential risks or that they took all reasonable steps to mitigate the effects of the grid failure, the court may still consider the event to be unforeseeable and grant force majeure protection.",
      "source": "target",
